:"<a href=\"https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-china-congress/us-senate-committee-sees-sweeping-china-legislation-in-mid-april-idUSL1N2LF1T3\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Farticle%2Fusa-china-congress%2Fus-senate-committee-sees-sweeping-china-legislation-in-mid-april-idUSL1N2LF1T3&d=1mBOIAkAA7%2FwaZBThmus2UpSq8GU1PbbWBdRLYKbGpc%3D&h=8514fd01\" data-ef-url=\"https://embed.lih.kg/frame?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.reuters.com%2Farticle%2Fusa-china-congress%2Fus-senate-committee-sees-sweeping-china-legislation-in-mid-april-idUSL1N2LF1T3&h=1553cdee\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-china-congress/us-senate-committee-sees-sweeping-china-legislation-in-mid-april-idUSL1N2LF1T3</a><br />\nWASHINGTON, March 17 (Reuters) - U.S. Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Bob Menendez said on Wednesday the panel plans to consider a sweeping package of China related legislation in mid-April, to allow time to craft legislation supported by both his fellow Democrats and Republicans.<br />\n<br />\nLawmakers had hoped to have a vote in the full Senate by mid-April, but Menendez said they needed more time so the two parties could work together.<br />\n<br />\nHe told a hearing on competing with China that the committee planned to mark up - debate and consider amendments to - the bill on April 14.<br />\n<br />\nSenate Majority Leader Chuck Schumer announced in February that he had directed lawmakers to write a package of legislation to counter China&rsquo;s rise, capitalizing on bipartisan hardline sentiment on Beijing in Congress.<br />\n<br />\nThe package would address economic competition with China in technology and other areas, as well as humanitarian and democratic values, such as the treatment of the minority Muslim Uighurs, <span class=\"x-large\"><strong>suppression of dissent in Hong Kong</strong></span> and aggression in the South China Sea. (Reporting by Patricia Zengerle Editing by Bill Berkrot)"}}